  "text": "Step 2. Normal case: X is a geometric quotient of a noetherian normal scheme X ′ by a finite group G [LMB00, 16.6.2]. It follows that X ′ is finitely parametrized: Since X ′ → X is finite, the pullback pr 1 : Step 3. Final step: By approximating X and p, we may assume that X is of finite type over Z (the reduction step in the proof of Chevalley's Theorem [CITATION_1] 8 .1] applies literally). In particular, X is noetherian and Nagata. If X red is an AF-scheme, then X is an AF-scheme as a consequence of Chevalley's Theorem. Therefore we may assume that X is reduced since X red is finitely parametrized. The normalization f : X ′ → X is finite since X is Nagata, hence X ′ is normal, noetherian and finitely parametrized. By step 2 we know that X ′ is representable by an AF-scheme. Let i :",
